results.name: Let a(1)=1. For n>1, a(n) is the greatest k such that a(1)a(2)...a(n-1) can be written in the form [x][y_1][y_2]...[y_k] where each y_i is of positive and equal length and for any i,j, y_i and y_j agree at every other term starting from the left (see example).
comment: Multiplication here denotes concatenation of strings. This is Gijswijt's sequence, A090822, except when checking if 'y' blocks are 'equal', we only compare every other term and ignore the others
link: F. J. van de Bult, D. C. Gijswijt, J. P. Linderman, N. J. A. Sloane and Allan Wilks, A Slow-Growing Sequence Defined by an Unusual Recurrence, J. Integer Sequences, Vol. 10 (2007), #07.1.2.
F. J. van de Bult, D. C. Gijswijt, J. P. Linderman, N. J. A. Sloane and Allan Wilks, A Slow-Growing Sequence Defined by an Unusual Recurrence [pdf, ps].
Index entries for sequences related to Gijswijt's sequence
example: For example, [1 2 3 4 5] and [1 0 3 100 5] count as being equal because both are of the form [1 ? 3 ? 5]
